8 //
9 // Attributor: An inter procedural (abstract) "attribute" deduction framework.
10 //
11 // The Attributor framework is an inter procedural abstract analysis (fixpoint
12 // iteration analysis). The goal is to allow easy deduction of new attributes as
13 // well as information exchange between abstract attributes in-flight.
14 //
15 // The Attributor class is the driver and the link between the various abstract
16 // attributes. The Attributor will iterate until a fixpoint state is reached by
17 // all abstract attributes in-flight, or until it will enforce a pessimistic fix
18 // point because an iteration limit is reached.
19 //
20 // Abstract attributes, derived from the AbstractAttribute class, actually
21 // describe properties of the code. They can correspond to actual LLVM-IR
22 // attributes, or they can be more general, ultimately unrelated to LLVM-IR
23 // attributes. The latter is useful when an abstract attributes provides
24 // information to other abstract attributes in-flight but we might not want to
25 // manifest the information. The Attributor allows to query in-flight abstract
26 // attributes through the `Attributor::getAAFor` method (see the method
27 // description for an example). If the method is used by an abstract attribute
28 // P, and it results in an abstract attribute Q, the Attributor will
29 // automatically capture a potential dependence from Q to P. This dependence
30 // will cause P to be reevaluated whenever Q changes in the future.
31 //
32 // The Attributor will only reevaluate abstract attributes that might have
33 // changed since the last iteration. That means that the Attribute will not
34 // revisit all instructions/blocks/functions in the module but only query
35 // an update from a subset of the abstract attributes.
36 //
37 // The update method `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl` is implemented by the
38 // specific "abstract attribute" subclasses. The method is invoked whenever the
39 // currently assumed state (see the AbstractState class) might not be valid
40 // anymore. This can, for example, happen if the state was dependent on another
41 // abstract attribute that changed. In every invocation, the update method has
42 // to adjust the internal state of an abstract attribute to a point that is
43 // justifiable by the underlying IR and the current state of abstract attributes
44 // in-flight. Since the IR is given and assumed to be valid, the information
45 // derived from it can be assumed to hold. However, information derived from
46 // other abstract attributes is conditional on various things. If the justifying
47 // state changed, the `updateImpl` has to revisit the situation and potentially
48 // find another justification or limit the optimistic assumes made.
49 //
50 // Change is the key in this framework. Until a state of no-change, thus a
51 // fixpoint, is reached, the Attributor will query the abstract attributes
52 // in-flight to re-evaluate their state. If the (current) state is too
53 // optimistic, hence it cannot be justified anymore through other abstract
54 // attributes or the state of the IR, the state of the abstract attribute will
55 // have to change. Generally, we assume abstract attribute state to be a finite
56 // height lattice and the update function to be monotone. However, these
57 // conditions are not enforced because the iteration limit will guarantee
58 // termination. If an optimistic fixpoint is reached, or a pessimistic fix
59 // point is enforced after a timeout, the abstract attributes are tasked to
60 // manifest their result in the IR for passes to come.
61 //
62 // Attribute manifestation is not mandatory. If desired, there is support to
63 // generate a single or multiple LLVM-IR attributes already in the helper struct
64 // IRAttribute. In the simplest case, a subclass inherits from IRAttribute with
65 // a proper Attribute::AttrKind as template parameter. The Attributor
66 // manifestation framework will then create and place a new attribute if it is
67 // allowed to do so (based on the abstract state). Other use cases can be
68 // achieved by overloading AbstractAttribute or IRAttribute methods.
69 //
70 //
71 // The "mechanics" of adding a new "abstract attribute":
72 // - Define a class (transitively) inheriting from AbstractAttribute and one
73 // (which could be the same) that (transitively) inherits from AbstractState.
74 // For the latter, consider the already available BooleanState and
75 // {Inc,Dec,Bit}IntegerState if they fit your needs, e.g., you require only a
76 // number tracking or bit-encoding.
77 // - Implement all pure methods. Also use overloading if the attribute is not
78 // conforming with the "default" behavior: A (set of) LLVM-IR attribute(s) for
79 // an argument, call site argument, function return value, or function. See
80 // the class and method descriptions for more information on the two
81 // "Abstract" classes and their respective methods.
82 // - Register opportunities for the new abstract attribute in the
83 // `Attributor::identifyDefaultAbstractAttributes` method if it should be
84 // counted as a 'default' attribute.
85 // - Add sufficient tests.
86 // - Add a Statistics object for bookkeeping. If it is a simple (set of)
87 // attribute(s) manifested through the Attributor manifestation framework, see
88 // the bookkeeping function in Attributor.cpp.
89 // - If instructions with a certain opcode are interesting to the attribute, add
90 // that opcode to the switch in `Attributor::identifyAbstractAttributes`. This
91 // will make it possible to query all those instructions through the
92 // `InformationCache::getOpcodeInstMapForFunction` interface and eliminate the
93 // need to traverse the IR repeatedly.
94 //

147 /// Helper to describe and deal with positions in the LLVM-IR.
148 ///
149 /// A position in the IR is described by an anchor value and an "offset" that
150 /// could be the argument number, for call sites and arguments, or an indicator
151 /// of the "position kind". The kinds, specified in the Kind enum below, include
152 /// the locations in the attribute list, i.a., function scope and return value,
153 /// as well as a distinction between call sites and functions. Finally, there
154 /// are floating values that do not have a corresponding attribute list
155 /// position.
156 struct IRPosition {
157 
158  /// The positions we distinguish in the IR.
159  enum Kind : char {
160  IRP_INVALID, ///< An invalid position.
161  IRP_FLOAT, ///< A position that is not associated with a spot suitable
162  ///< for attributes. This could be any value or instruction.
163  IRP_RETURNED, ///< An attribute for the function return value.
164  IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED, ///< An attribute for a call site return value.
165  IRP_FUNCTION, ///< An attribute for a function (scope).
166  IRP_CALL_SITE, ///< An attribute for a call site (function scope).
167  IRP_ARGUMENT, ///< An attribute for a function argument.
168  IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT, ///< An attribute for a call site argument.
169  };
170 
171  /// Default constructor available to create invalid positions implicitly. All
172  /// other positions need to be created explicitly through the appropriate
173  /// static member function.
174  IRPosition() : Enc(nullptr, ENC_VALUE) { verify(); }
175 
176  /// Create a position describing the value of \p V.
177  static const IRPosition value(const Value &V) {
178  if (auto *Arg = dyn_cast<Argument>(&V))
179  return IRPosition::argument(*Arg);
180  if (auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&V))
181  return IRPosition::callsite_returned(*CB);
182  return IRPosition(const_cast<Value &>(V), IRP_FLOAT);
183  }
184 
185  /// Create a position describing the function scope of \p F.
186  static const IRPosition function(const Function &F) {
187  return IRPosition(const_cast<Function &>(F), IRP_FUNCTION);
188  }
189 
190  /// Create a position describing the returned value of \p F.
191  static const IRPosition returned(const Function &F) {
192  return IRPosition(const_cast<Function &>(F), IRP_RETURNED);
193  }
194 
195  /// Create a position describing the argument \p Arg.
196  static const IRPosition argument(const Argument &Arg) {
197  return IRPosition(const_cast<Argument &>(Arg), IRP_ARGUMENT);
198  }
199 
200  /// Create a position describing the function scope of \p CB.
201  static const IRPosition callsite_function(const CallBase &CB) {
202  return IRPosition(const_cast<CallBase &>(CB), IRP_CALL_SITE);
203  }
204 
205  /// Create a position describing the returned value of \p CB.
206  static const IRPosition callsite_returned(const CallBase &CB) {
207  return IRPosition(const_cast<CallBase &>(CB), IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED);
208  }
209 
210  /// Create a position describing the argument of \p CB at position \p ArgNo.
211  static const IRPosition callsite_argument(const CallBase &CB,
212  unsigned ArgNo) {
213  return IRPosition(const_cast<Use &>(CB.getArgOperandUse(ArgNo)),
214  IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT);
215  }
216 
217  /// Create a position describing the argument of \p ACS at position \p ArgNo.
218  static const IRPosition callsite_argument(AbstractCallSite ACS,
219  unsigned ArgNo) {
220  if (ACS.getNumArgOperands() <= ArgNo)
221  return IRPosition();
222  int CSArgNo = ACS.getCallArgOperandNo(ArgNo);
223  if (CSArgNo >= 0)
224  return IRPosition::callsite_argument(
225  cast<CallBase>(*ACS.getInstruction()), CSArgNo);
226  return IRPosition();
227  }
228 
229  /// Create a position with function scope matching the "context" of \p IRP.
230  /// If \p IRP is a call site (see isAnyCallSitePosition()) then the result
231  /// will be a call site position, otherwise the function position of the
232  /// associated function.
233  static const IRPosition function_scope(const IRPosition &IRP) {
234  if (IRP.isAnyCallSitePosition()) {
235  return IRPosition::callsite_function(
236  cast<CallBase>(IRP.getAnchorValue()));
237  }
238  assert(IRP.getAssociatedFunction());
239  return IRPosition::function(*IRP.getAssociatedFunction());
240  }

242  bool operator==(const IRPosition &RHS) const { return Enc == RHS.Enc; }
243  bool operator!=(const IRPosition &RHS) const { return !(*this == RHS); }

245  /// Return the value this abstract attribute is anchored with.
246  ///
247  /// The anchor value might not be the associated value if the latter is not
248  /// sufficient to determine where arguments will be manifested. This is, so
249  /// far, only the case for call site arguments as the value is not sufficient
250  /// to pinpoint them. Instead, we can use the call site as an anchor.
251  Value &getAnchorValue() const {
252  switch (getEncodingBits()) {
253  case ENC_VALUE:
254  case ENC_RETURNED_VALUE:
255  case ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION:
256  return *getAsValuePtr();
257  case ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE:
258  return *(getAsUsePtr()->getUser());
259  default:
260  llvm_unreachable("Unkown encoding!");
261  };
262  }
263 
264  /// Return the associated function, if any.
265  Function *getAssociatedFunction() const {
266  if (auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue()))
267  return CB->getCalledFunction();
268  return getAnchorScope();
269  }
270 
271  /// Return the associated argument, if any.
272  Argument *getAssociatedArgument() const;
273 
274  /// Return true if the position refers to a function interface, that is the
275  /// function scope, the function return, or an argument.
276  bool isFnInterfaceKind() const {
277  switch (getPositionKind()) {
278  case IRPosition::IRP_FUNCTION:
279  case IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED:
280  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
281  return true;
282  default:
283  return false;
284  }
285  }
286 
287  /// Return the Function surrounding the anchor value.
288  Function *getAnchorScope() const {
289  Value &V = getAnchorValue();
290  if (isa<Function>(V))
291  return &cast<Function>(V);
292  if (isa<Argument>(V))
293  return cast<Argument>(V).getParent();
294  if (isa<Instruction>(V))
295  return cast<Instruction>(V).getFunction();
296  return nullptr;
297  }
298 
299  /// Return the context instruction, if any.
300  Instruction *getCtxI() const {
301  Value &V = getAnchorValue();
302  if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(&V))
303  return I;
304  if (auto *Arg = dyn_cast<Argument>(&V))
305  if (!Arg->getParent()->isDeclaration())
306  return &Arg->getParent()->getEntryBlock().front();
307  if (auto *F = dyn_cast<Function>(&V))
308  if (!F->isDeclaration())
309  return &(F->getEntryBlock().front());
310  return nullptr;
311  }
312 
313  /// Return the value this abstract attribute is associated with.
314  Value &getAssociatedValue() const {
315  if (getArgNo() < 0 || isa<Argument>(&getAnchorValue()))
316  return getAnchorValue();
317  assert(isa<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue()) && "Expected a call base!");
318  return *cast<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue())->getArgOperand(getArgNo());
319  }
320 
321  /// Return the type this abstract attribute is associated with.
322  Type *getAssociatedType() const {
323  if (getPositionKind() == IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED)
324  return getAssociatedFunction()->getReturnType();
325  return getAssociatedValue().getType();
326  }
327 
328  /// Return the argument number of the associated value if it is an argument or
329  /// call site argument, otherwise a negative value.
330  int getArgNo() const {
331  switch (getPositionKind()) {
332  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
333  return cast<Argument>(getAsValuePtr())->getArgNo();
334  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT: {
335  Use &U = *getAsUsePtr();
336  return cast<CallBase>(U.getUser())->getArgOperandNo(&U);
337  }
338  default:
339  return -1;
340  }
341  }
342 
343  /// Return the index in the attribute list for this position.
344  unsigned getAttrIdx() const {
345  switch (getPositionKind()) {
346  case IRPosition::IRP_INVALID:
347  case IRPosition::IRP_FLOAT:
348  break;
349  case IRPosition::IRP_FUNCTION:
350  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE:
351  return AttributeList::FunctionIndex;
352  case IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED:
353  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
354  return AttributeList::ReturnIndex;
355  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
356  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
357  return getArgNo() + AttributeList::FirstArgIndex;
358  }
359  llvm_unreachable(
360  "There is no attribute index for a floating or invalid position!");
361  }
362 
363  /// Return the associated position kind.
364  Kind getPositionKind() const {
365  char EncodingBits = getEncodingBits();
366  if (EncodingBits == ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE)
367  return IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT;
368  if (EncodingBits == ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION)
369  return IRP_FLOAT;
370 
371  Value *V = getAsValuePtr();
372  if (!V)
373  return IRP_INVALID;
374  if (isa<Argument>(V))
375  return IRP_ARGUMENT;
376  if (isa<Function>(V))
377  return isReturnPosition(EncodingBits) ? IRP_RETURNED : IRP_FUNCTION;
378  if (isa<CallBase>(V))
379  return isReturnPosition(EncodingBits) ? IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED
380  : IRP_CALL_SITE;
381  return IRP_FLOAT;
382  }

387  /// Return true if any kind in \p AKs existing in the IR at a position that
388  /// will affect this one. See also getAttrs(...).
389  /// \param IgnoreSubsumingPositions Flag to determine if subsuming positions,
390  /// e.g., the function position if this is an

396  /// Return the attributes of any kind in \p AKs existing in the IR at a
397  /// position that will affect this one. While each position can only have a
398  /// single attribute of any kind in \p AKs, there are "subsuming" positions
399  /// that could have an attribute as well. This method returns all attributes
400  /// found in \p Attrs.
401  /// \param IgnoreSubsumingPositions Flag to determine if subsuming positions,
402  /// e.g., the function position if this is an
403  /// argument position, should be ignored.
404  void getAttrs(ArrayRef<Attribute::AttrKind> AKs,
405  SmallVectorImpl<Attribute> &Attrs,
406  bool IgnoreSubsumingPositions = false,
407  Attributor *A = nullptr) const;

409  /// Remove the attribute of kind \p AKs existing in the IR at this position.
410  void removeAttrs(ArrayRef<Attribute::AttrKind> AKs) const {
411  if (getPositionKind() == IRP_INVALID || getPositionKind() == IRP_FLOAT)
412  return;
413 
414  AttributeList AttrList;
415  auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue());
416  if (CB)
417  AttrList = CB->getAttributes();
418  else
419  AttrList = getAssociatedFunction()->getAttributes();
420 
421  LLVMContext &Ctx = getAnchorValue().getContext();
422  for (Attribute::AttrKind AK : AKs)
423  AttrList = AttrList.removeAttribute(Ctx, getAttrIdx(), AK);
424 
425  if (CB)
426  CB->setAttributes(AttrList);
427  else
428  getAssociatedFunction()->setAttributes(AttrList);
429  }

432  switch (getPositionKind()) {
433  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE:
434  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
435  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
436  return true;
437  default:
438  return false;
439  }
440  }

456  /// IRPosition anchored at \p AnchorVal with kind/argument numbet \p PK.
457  explicit IRPosition(Value &AnchorVal, Kind PK) {
458  switch (PK) {
459  case IRPosition::IRP_INVALID:
460  llvm_unreachable("Cannot create invalid IRP with an anchor value!");
461  break;
462  case IRPosition::IRP_FLOAT:
463  // Special case for floating functions.
464  if (isa<Function>(AnchorVal))
465  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION};
466  else
467  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_VALUE};
468  break;
469  case IRPosition::IRP_FUNCTION:
470  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE:
471  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_VALUE};
472  break;
473  case IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED:
474  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
475  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_RETURNED_VALUE};
476  break;
477  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
478  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_VALUE};
479  break;
480  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
481  llvm_unreachable(
482  "Cannot create call site argument IRP with an anchor value!");
483  break;
484  }
485  verify();
486  }
487 
488  /// IRPosition for the use \p U. The position kind \p PK needs to be
489  /// IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT, the anchor value is the user, the associated value
490  /// the used value.
491  explicit IRPosition(Use &U, Kind PK) {
492  assert(PK == IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT &&
493  "Use constructor is for call site arguments only!");
494  Enc = {&U, ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE};
495  verify();
496  }

511  /// Return the underlying pointer as Value *, valid for all positions but
512  /// IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT.

515  "Not a value pointer!");

527  /// Return true if \p EncodingBits describe a returned or call site returned
528  /// position.
529  static bool isReturnPosition(char EncodingBits) {
530  return EncodingBits == ENC_RETURNED_VALUE;
531  }
532 
533  /// Return true if the encoding bits describe a returned or call site returned
534  /// position.
535  bool isReturnPosition() const { return isReturnPosition(getEncodingBits()); }
536 
537  /// The encoding of the IRPosition is a combination of a pointer and two
538  /// encoding bits. The values of the encoding bits are defined in the enum
539  /// below. The pointer is either a Value* (for the first three encoding bit
540  /// combinations) or Use* (for ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE).
541  ///
542  ///{
543  enum {
544  ENC_VALUE = 0b00,
545  ENC_RETURNED_VALUE = 0b01,
546  ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION = 0b10,
547  ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE = 0b11,
548  };
549 
550  // Reserve the maximal amount of bits so there is no need to mask out the
551  // remaining ones. We will not encode anything else in the pointer anyway.
552  static constexpr int NumEncodingBits =
553  PointerLikeTypeTraits<void *>::NumLowBitsAvailable;
554  static_assert(NumEncodingBits >= 2, "At least two bits are required!");
555 
556  /// The pointer with the encoding bits.
557  PointerIntPair<void *, NumEncodingBits, char> Enc;
558  ///}
559 
560  /// Return the encoding bits.
561  char getEncodingBits() const { return Enc.getInt(); }
562 };

572 /// A visitor class for IR positions.
573 ///
574 /// Given a position P, the SubsumingPositionIterator allows to visit "subsuming
575 /// positions" wrt. attributes/information. Thus, if a piece of information
576 /// holds for a subsuming position, it also holds for the position P.
577 ///
578 /// The subsuming positions always include the initial position and then,
579 /// depending on the position kind, additionally the following ones:
580 /// - for IRP_RETURNED:
581 /// - the function (IRP_FUNCTION)
582 /// - for IRP_ARGUMENT:
583 /// - the function (IRP_FUNCTION)
584 /// - for IRP_CALL_SITE:
585 /// - the callee (IRP_FUNCTION), if known
586 /// - for IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
587 /// - the callee (IRP_RETURNED), if known
588 /// - the call site (IRP_FUNCTION)
589 /// - the callee (IRP_FUNCTION), if known
590 /// - for IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
591 /// - the argument of the callee (IRP_ARGUMENT), if known
592 /// - the callee (IRP_FUNCTION), if known
593 /// - the position the call site argument is associated with if it is not
594 /// anchored to the call site, e.g., if it is an argument then the argument
595 /// (IRP_ARGUMENT)
596 class SubsumingPositionIterator {
597  SmallVector<IRPosition, 4> IRPositions;
598  using iterator = decltype(IRPositions)::iterator;
599 
600 public:
601  SubsumingPositionIterator(const IRPosition &IRP);
602  iterator begin() { return IRPositions.begin(); }
603  iterator end() { return IRPositions.end(); }
604 };

606 /// Wrapper for FunctoinAnalysisManager.
607 struct AnalysisGetter {
608  template <typename Analysis>

610  if (!FAM || !F.getParent())
611  return nullptr;
612  return &FAM->getResult<Analysis>(const_cast<Function &>(F));
613  }
614 
615  AnalysisGetter(FunctionAnalysisManager &FAM) : FAM(&FAM) {}
616  AnalysisGetter() {}
617

622 /// Data structure to hold cached (LLVM-IR) information.
623 ///
624 /// All attributes are given an InformationCache object at creation time to
625 /// avoid inspection of the IR by all of them individually. This default
626 /// InformationCache will hold information required by 'default' attributes,
627 /// thus the ones deduced when Attributor::identifyDefaultAbstractAttributes(..)
628 /// is called.
629 ///
630 /// If custom abstract attributes, registered manually through
631 /// Attributor::registerAA(...), need more information, especially if it is not
632 /// reusable, it is advised to inherit from the InformationCache and cast the
633 /// instance down in the abstract attributes.
634 struct InformationCache {
635  InformationCache(const Module &M, AnalysisGetter &AG,
636  BumpPtrAllocator &Allocator, SetVector<Function *> *CGSCC)
637  : DL(M.getDataLayout()), Allocator(Allocator),
638  Explorer(
639  /* ExploreInterBlock */ true, /* ExploreCFGForward */ true,
640  /* ExploreCFGBackward */ true,
641  /* LIGetter */
642  [&](const Function &F) { return AG.getAnalysis<LoopAnalysis>(F); },
643  /* DTGetter */
644  [&](const Function &F) {
645  return AG.getAnalysis<DominatorTreeAnalysis>(F);
646  },
647  /* PDTGetter */
648  [&](const Function &F) {
649  return AG.getAnalysis<PostDominatorTreeAnalysis>(F);
650  }),
651  AG(AG), CGSCC(CGSCC) {}
652 
653  ~InformationCache() {
654  // The FunctionInfo objects are allocated via a BumpPtrAllocator, we call
655  // the destructor manually.
656  for (auto &It : FuncInfoMap)
657  It.getSecond()->~FunctionInfo();
658  }

782 /// The fixpoint analysis framework that orchestrates the attribute deduction.
783 ///
784 /// The Attributor provides a general abstract analysis framework (guided
785 /// fixpoint iteration) as well as helper functions for the deduction of
786 /// (LLVM-IR) attributes. However, also other code properties can be deduced,
787 /// propagated, and ultimately manifested through the Attributor framework. This
788 /// is particularly useful if these properties interact with attributes and a
789 /// co-scheduled deduction allows to improve the solution. Even if not, thus if
790 /// attributes/properties are completely isolated, they should use the
791 /// Attributor framework to reduce the number of fixpoint iteration frameworks
792 /// in the code base. Note that the Attributor design makes sure that isolated
793 /// attributes are not impacted, in any way, by others derived at the same time
794 /// if there is no cross-reasoning performed.
795 ///
796 /// The public facing interface of the Attributor is kept simple and basically
797 /// allows abstract attributes to one thing, query abstract attributes
798 /// in-flight. There are two reasons to do this:
799 /// a) The optimistic state of one abstract attribute can justify an
800 /// optimistic state of another, allowing to framework to end up with an
801 /// optimistic (=best possible) fixpoint instead of one based solely on
802 /// information in the IR.
803 /// b) This avoids reimplementing various kinds of lookups, e.g., to check
804 /// for existing IR attributes, in favor of a single lookups interface
805 /// provided by an abstract attribute subclass.
806 ///
807 /// NOTE: The mechanics of adding a new "concrete" abstract attribute are
808 /// described in the file comment.
809 struct Attributor {
810  /// Constructor
811  ///
812  /// \param Functions The set of functions we are deriving attributes for.
813  /// \param InfoCache Cache to hold various information accessible for
814  /// the abstract attributes.
815  /// \param CGUpdater Helper to update an underlying call graph.
816  /// \param Allowed If not null, a set limiting the attribute opportunities.
817  Attributor(SetVector<Function *> &Functions, InformationCache &InfoCache,
818  CallGraphUpdater &CGUpdater,
819  DenseSet<const char *> *Allowed = nullptr)
820  : Allocator(InfoCache.Allocator), Functions(Functions),
821  InfoCache(InfoCache), CGUpdater(CGUpdater), Allowed(Allowed) {}
822 
823  ~Attributor();
824 
825  /// Run the analyses until a fixpoint is reached or enforced (timeout).
826  ///
827  /// The attributes registered with this Attributor can be used after as long
828  /// as the Attributor is not destroyed (it owns the attributes now).
829  ///
830  /// \Returns CHANGED if the IR was changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
831  ChangeStatus run();
832 
833  /// Lookup an abstract attribute of type \p AAType at position \p IRP. While
834  /// no abstract attribute is found equivalent positions are checked, see
835  /// SubsumingPositionIterator. Thus, the returned abstract attribute
836  /// might be anchored at a different position, e.g., the callee if \p IRP is a
837  /// call base.
838  ///
839  /// This method is the only (supported) way an abstract attribute can retrieve
840  /// information from another abstract attribute. As an example, take an
841  /// abstract attribute that determines the memory access behavior for a
842  /// argument (readnone, readonly, ...). It should use `getAAFor` to get the
843  /// most optimistic information for other abstract attributes in-flight, e.g.
844  /// the one reasoning about the "captured" state for the argument or the one
845  /// reasoning on the memory access behavior of the function as a whole.
846  ///
847  /// If the flag \p TrackDependence is set to false the dependence from
848  /// \p QueryingAA to the return abstract attribute is not automatically
849  /// recorded. This should only be used if the caller will record the
850  /// dependence explicitly if necessary, thus if it the returned abstract
851  /// attribute is used for reasoning. To record the dependences explicitly use
852  /// the `Attributor::recordDependence` method.
853  template <typename AAType>
854  const AAType &getAAFor(const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA,
855  const IRPosition &IRP, bool TrackDependence = true,
856  DepClassTy DepClass = DepClassTy::REQUIRED) {
857  return getOrCreateAAFor<AAType>(IRP, &QueryingAA, TrackDependence, DepClass,
858  /* ForceUpdate */ false);
859  }
860 
861  /// Similar to getAAFor but the return abstract attribute will be updated (via
862  /// `AbstractAttribute::update`) even if it is found in the cache. This is
863  /// especially useful for AAIsDead as changes in liveness can make updates
864  /// possible/useful that were not happening before as the abstract attribute
865  /// was assumed dead.
866  template <typename AAType>
867  const AAType &getAndUpdateAAFor(const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA,
868  const IRPosition &IRP,
869  bool TrackDependence = true,
870  DepClassTy DepClass = DepClassTy::REQUIRED) {
871  return getOrCreateAAFor<AAType>(IRP, &QueryingAA, TrackDependence, DepClass,
872  /* ForceUpdate */ true);
873  }
874 
875  /// The version of getAAFor that allows to omit a querying abstract
876  /// attribute. Using this after Attributor started running is restricted to
877  /// only the Attributor itself. Initial seeding of AAs can be done via this
878  /// function.
879  template <typename AAType>
880  const AAType &getOrCreateAAFor(const IRPosition &IRP,
881  const AbstractAttribute *QueryingAA = nullptr,
882  bool TrackDependence = false,
883  DepClassTy DepClass = DepClassTy::OPTIONAL,
884  bool ForceUpdate = false) {
885  if (AAType *AAPtr = lookupAAFor<AAType>(IRP, QueryingAA, TrackDependence)) {
886  if (ForceUpdate)
887  updateAA(*AAPtr);
888  return *AAPtr;
889  }
890 
891  // No matching attribute found, create one.
892  // Use the static create method.
893  auto &AA = AAType::createForPosition(IRP, *this);
894 
895  // If we are currenty seeding attributes, enforce seeding rules.
896  if (SeedingPeriod && !shouldSeedAttribute(AA)) {
897  AA.getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
898  return AA;
899  }
900 
901  registerAA(AA);
902 
903  // For now we ignore naked and optnone functions.
904  bool Invalidate = Allowed && !Allowed->count(&AAType::ID);
905  const Function *FnScope = IRP.getAnchorScope();
906  if (FnScope)
907  Invalidate |= FnScope->hasFnAttribute(Attribute::Naked) ||
908  FnScope->hasFnAttribute(Attribute::OptimizeNone);
909 
910  // Bootstrap the new attribute with an initial update to propagate
911  // information, e.g., function -> call site. If it is not on a given
912  // Allowed we will not perform updates at all.
913  if (Invalidate) {
914  AA.getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
915  return AA;
916  }
917 
918  AA.initialize(*this);
919 
920  // We can initialize (=look at) code outside the current function set but
921  // not call update because that would again spawn new abstract attributes in
922  // potentially unconnected code regions (=SCCs).
923  if (FnScope && !Functions.count(const_cast<Function *>(FnScope))) {
924  AA.getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
925  return AA;
926  }
927 
928  // Allow seeded attributes to declare dependencies.
929  // Remember the seeding state.
930  bool OldSeedingPeriod = SeedingPeriod;
931  SeedingPeriod = false;
932 
933  updateAA(AA);
934 
935  SeedingPeriod = OldSeedingPeriod;
936 
937  if (TrackDependence && AA.getState().isValidState())
938  recordDependence(AA, const_cast<AbstractAttribute &>(*QueryingAA),
939  DepClass);
940  return AA;
941  }
942 
943  /// Return the attribute of \p AAType for \p IRP if existing. This also allows
944  /// non-AA users lookup.
945  template <typename AAType>
946  AAType *lookupAAFor(const IRPosition &IRP,
947  const AbstractAttribute *QueryingAA = nullptr,
948  bool TrackDependence = false,
949  DepClassTy DepClass = DepClassTy::OPTIONAL) {
950  static_assert(std::is_base_of<AbstractAttribute, AAType>::value,
951  "Cannot query an attribute with a type not derived from "
952  "'AbstractAttribute'!");
953  assert((QueryingAA || !TrackDependence) &&
954  "Cannot track dependences without a QueryingAA!");
955 
956  // Lookup the abstract attribute of type AAType. If found, return it after
957  // registering a dependence of QueryingAA on the one returned attribute.
958  AbstractAttribute *AAPtr = AAMap.lookup({&AAType::ID, IRP});
959  if (!AAPtr)
960  return nullptr;
961 
962  AAType *AA = static_cast<AAType *>(AAPtr);
963 
964  // Do not register a dependence on an attribute with an invalid state.
965  if (TrackDependence && AA->getState().isValidState())
966  recordDependence(*AA, const_cast<AbstractAttribute &>(*QueryingAA),
967  DepClass);
968  return AA;
969  }
970 
971  /// Explicitly record a dependence from \p FromAA to \p ToAA, that is if
972  /// \p FromAA changes \p ToAA should be updated as well.
973  ///
974  /// This method should be used in conjunction with the `getAAFor` method and
975  /// with the TrackDependence flag passed to the method set to false. This can
976  /// be beneficial to avoid false dependences but it requires the users of
977  /// `getAAFor` to explicitly record true dependences through this method.
978  /// The \p DepClass flag indicates if the dependence is striclty necessary.
979  /// That means for required dependences, if \p FromAA changes to an invalid
980  /// state, \p ToAA can be moved to a pessimistic fixpoint because it required
981  /// information from \p FromAA but none are available anymore.
982  void recordDependence(const AbstractAttribute &FromAA,
983  const AbstractAttribute &ToAA, DepClassTy DepClass);
984 
985  /// Introduce a new abstract attribute into the fixpoint analysis.
986  ///
987  /// Note that ownership of the attribute is given to the Attributor. It will
988  /// invoke delete for the Attributor on destruction of the Attributor.
989  ///
990  /// Attributes are identified by their IR position (AAType::getIRPosition())
991  /// and the address of their static member (see AAType::ID).
992  template <typename AAType> AAType &registerAA(AAType &AA) {
993  static_assert(std::is_base_of<AbstractAttribute, AAType>::value,
994  "Cannot register an attribute with a type not derived from "
995  "'AbstractAttribute'!");
996  // Put the attribute in the lookup map structure and the container we use to
997  // keep track of all attributes.
998  const IRPosition &IRP = AA.getIRPosition();
999  AbstractAttribute *&AAPtr = AAMap[{&AAType::ID, IRP}];
1000 
1001  assert(!AAPtr && "Attribute already in map!");
1002  AAPtr = &AA;
1003 
1004  AllAbstractAttributes.push_back(&AA);
1005  return AA;
1006  }

1061  /// Record that \p U is to be replaces with \p NV after information was
1062  /// manifested. This also triggers deletion of trivially dead istructions.
1063  bool changeUseAfterManifest(Use &U, Value &NV) {
1064  Value *&V = ToBeChangedUses[&U];
1065  if (V && (V->stripPointerCasts() == NV.stripPointerCasts() ||
1066  isa_and_nonnull<UndefValue>(V)))
1067  return false;
1068  assert((!V || V == &NV || isa<UndefValue>(NV)) &&
1069  "Use was registered twice for replacement with different values!");
1070  V = &NV;
1071  return true;
1072  }

1078  bool ChangeDroppable = true) {

1080  for (auto &U : V.uses())
1081  if (ChangeDroppable || !U.getUser()->isDroppable())
1082  Changed |= changeUseAfterManifest(U, NV);
1083 
1084  return Changed;
1085  }

1156  /// Helper struct used in the communication between an abstract attribute (AA)
1157  /// that wants to change the signature of a function and the Attributor which
1158  /// applies the changes. The struct is partially initialized with the
1159  /// information from the AA (see the constructor). All other members are
1160  /// provided by the Attributor prior to invoking any callbacks.
1161  struct ArgumentReplacementInfo {
1162  /// Callee repair callback type
1163  ///
1164  /// The function repair callback is invoked once to rewire the replacement
1165  /// arguments in the body of the new function. The argument replacement info
1166  /// is passed, as build from the registerFunctionSignatureRewrite call, as
1167  /// well as the replacement function and an iteratore to the first
1168  /// replacement argument.
1169  using CalleeRepairCBTy = std::function<void(
1170  const ArgumentReplacementInfo &, Function &, Function::arg_iterator)>;
1171 
1172  /// Abstract call site (ACS) repair callback type
1173  ///
1174  /// The abstract call site repair callback is invoked once on every abstract
1175  /// call site of the replaced function (\see ReplacedFn). The callback needs
1176  /// to provide the operands for the call to the new replacement function.
1177  /// The number and type of the operands appended to the provided vector
1178  /// (second argument) is defined by the number and types determined through
1179  /// the replacement type vector (\see ReplacementTypes). The first argument
1180  /// is the ArgumentReplacementInfo object registered with the Attributor
1181  /// through the registerFunctionSignatureRewrite call.
1182  using ACSRepairCBTy =
1183  std::function<void(const ArgumentReplacementInfo &, AbstractCallSite,
1184  SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &)>;
1185 
1186  /// Simple getters, see the corresponding members for details.
1187  ///{
1188 
1189  Attributor &getAttributor() const { return A; }
1190  const Function &getReplacedFn() const { return ReplacedFn; }
1191  const Argument &getReplacedArg() const { return ReplacedArg; }
1192  unsigned getNumReplacementArgs() const { return ReplacementTypes.size(); }
1193  const SmallVectorImpl<Type *> &getReplacementTypes() const {
1194  return ReplacementTypes;
1195  }
1196 
1197  ///}
1198 
1199  private:

1444 /// An interface to query the internal state of an abstract attribute.
1445 ///
1446 /// The abstract state is a minimal interface that allows the Attributor to
1447 /// communicate with the abstract attributes about their internal state without
1448 /// enforcing or exposing implementation details, e.g., the (existence of an)
1449 /// underlying lattice.
1450 ///
1451 /// It is sufficient to be able to query if a state is (1) valid or invalid, (2)
1452 /// at a fixpoint, and to indicate to the state that (3) an optimistic fixpoint
1453 /// was reached or (4) a pessimistic fixpoint was enforced.
1454 ///
1455 /// All methods need to be implemented by the subclass. For the common use case,
1456 /// a single boolean state or a bit-encoded state, the BooleanState and
1457 /// {Inc,Dec,Bit}IntegerState classes are already provided. An abstract
1458 /// attribute can inherit from them to get the abstract state interface and
1459 /// additional methods to directly modify the state based if needed. See the
1460 /// class comments for help.
1461 struct AbstractState {
1462  virtual ~AbstractState() {}
1463 
1464  /// Return if this abstract state is in a valid state. If false, no
1465  /// information provided should be used.
1466  virtual bool isValidState() const = 0;
1467 
1468  /// Return if this abstract state is fixed, thus does not need to be updated
1469  /// if information changes as it cannot change itself.
1470  virtual bool isAtFixpoint() const = 0;
1471 
1472  /// Indicate that the abstract state should converge to the optimistic state.
1473  ///
1474  /// This will usually make the optimistically assumed state the known to be
1475  /// true state.
1476  ///
1477  /// \returns ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED as the assumed value should not change.
1478  virtual ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() = 0;
1479 
1480  /// Indicate that the abstract state should converge to the pessimistic state.
1481  ///
1482  /// This will usually revert the optimistically assumed state to the known to
1483  /// be true state.
1484  ///
1485  /// \returns ChangeStatus::CHANGED as the assumed value may change.
1486  virtual ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() = 0;
1487 };

1489 /// Simple state with integers encoding.
1490 ///
1491 /// The interface ensures that the assumed bits are always a subset of the known
1492 /// bits. Users can only add known bits and, except through adding known bits,
1493 /// they can only remove assumed bits. This should guarantee monotoniticy and
1494 /// thereby the existence of a fixpoint (if used corretly). The fixpoint is
1495 /// reached when the assumed and known state/bits are equal. Users can
1496 /// force/inidicate a fixpoint. If an optimistic one is indicated, the known
1497 /// state will catch up with the assumed one, for a pessimistic fixpoint it is
1498 /// the other way around.
1499 template <typename base_ty, base_ty BestState, base_ty WorstState>
1500 struct IntegerStateBase : public AbstractState {
1501  using base_t = base_ty;
1502 
1503  IntegerStateBase() {}
1504  IntegerStateBase(base_t Assumed) : Assumed(Assumed) {}
1505 
1506  /// Return the best possible representable state.
1507  static constexpr base_t getBestState() { return BestState; }
1508  static constexpr base_t getBestState(const IntegerStateBase &) {
1509  return getBestState();
1510  }
1511 
1512  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
1513  static constexpr base_t getWorstState() { return WorstState; }
1514  static constexpr base_t getWorstState(const IntegerStateBase &) {
1515  return getWorstState();
1516  }
1517 
1518  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
1519  /// NOTE: For now we simply pretend that the worst possible state is invalid.
1520  bool isValidState() const override { return Assumed != getWorstState(); }
1521 
1522  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
1523  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return Assumed == Known; }
1524 
1525  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
1526  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
1527  Known = Assumed;
1528  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
1529  }
1530 
1531  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
1532  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
1533  Assumed = Known;
1534  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
1535  }
1536 
1537  /// Return the known state encoding
1538  base_t getKnown() const { return Known; }
1539 
1540  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
1541  base_t getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
1542 
1543  /// Equality for IntegerStateBase.
1544  bool
1545  operator==(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) const {
1546  return this->getAssumed() == R.getAssumed() &&
1547  this->getKnown() == R.getKnown();
1548  }
1549 
1550  /// Inequality for IntegerStateBase.
1551  bool
1552  operator!=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) const {
1553  return !(*this == R);
1554  }
1555 
1556  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
1557  /// intended that only information assumed in both states will be assumed in
1558  /// this one afterwards.
1559  void operator^=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
1560  handleNewAssumedValue(R.getAssumed());
1561  }
1562 
1563  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
1564  /// intended that information known in either state will be known in
1565  /// this one afterwards.
1566  void operator+=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
1567  handleNewKnownValue(R.getKnown());
1568  }
1569 
1570  void operator|=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
1571  joinOR(R.getAssumed(), R.getKnown());
1572  }
1573 
1574  void operator&=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
1575  joinAND(R.getAssumed(), R.getKnown());
1576  }
1577 
1578 protected:
1579  /// Handle a new assumed value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
1580  virtual void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) = 0;
1581 
1582  /// Handle a new known value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
1583  virtual void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) = 0;
1584 
1585  /// Handle a value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
1586  virtual void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) = 0;
1587 
1588  /// Handle a new assumed value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
1589  virtual void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) = 0;
1590 
1591  /// The known state encoding in an integer of type base_t.
1592  base_t Known = getWorstState();
1593 
1594  /// The assumed state encoding in an integer of type base_t.
1595  base_t Assumed = getBestState();
1596 };

1598 /// Specialization of the integer state for a bit-wise encoding.
1599 template <typename base_ty = uint32_t, base_ty BestState = ~base_ty(0),
1600  base_ty WorstState = 0>
1601 struct BitIntegerState
1602  : public IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> {
1603  using base_t = base_ty;
1604 
1605  /// Return true if the bits set in \p BitsEncoding are "known bits".
1606  bool isKnown(base_t BitsEncoding) const {
1607  return (this->Known & BitsEncoding) == BitsEncoding;
1608  }
1609 
1610  /// Return true if the bits set in \p BitsEncoding are "assumed bits".
1611  bool isAssumed(base_t BitsEncoding) const {
1612  return (this->Assumed & BitsEncoding) == BitsEncoding;
1613  }
1614 
1615  /// Add the bits in \p BitsEncoding to the "known bits".
1616  BitIntegerState &addKnownBits(base_t Bits) {
1617  // Make sure we never miss any "known bits".
1618  this->Assumed |= Bits;
1619  this->Known |= Bits;
1620  return *this;
1621  }
1622 
1623  /// Remove the bits in \p BitsEncoding from the "assumed bits" if not known.
1624  BitIntegerState &removeAssumedBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
1625  return intersectAssumedBits(~BitsEncoding);
1626  }
1627 
1628  /// Remove the bits in \p BitsEncoding from the "known bits".
1629  BitIntegerState &removeKnownBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
1630  this->Known = (this->Known & ~BitsEncoding);
1631  return *this;
1632  }
1633 
1634  /// Keep only "assumed bits" also set in \p BitsEncoding but all known ones.
1635  BitIntegerState &intersectAssumedBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
1636  // Make sure we never loose any "known bits".
1637  this->Assumed = (this->Assumed & BitsEncoding) | this->Known;
1638  return *this;
1639  }
1640 
1641 private:
1642  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
1643  intersectAssumedBits(Value);
1644  }
1645  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override { addKnownBits(Value); }
1646  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
1647  this->Known |= KnownValue;
1648  this->Assumed |= AssumedValue;
1649  }
1650  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
1651  this->Known &= KnownValue;
1652  this->Assumed &= AssumedValue;
1653  }
1654 };

1784 struct IntegerRangeState : public AbstractState {
1785 
1786  /// Bitwidth of the associated value.
1787  uint32_t BitWidth;
1788 
1789  /// State representing assumed range, initially set to empty.
1790  ConstantRange Assumed;
1791 
1792  /// State representing known range, initially set to [-inf, inf].
1793  ConstantRange Known;
1794 
1795  IntegerRangeState(uint32_t BitWidth)
1796  : BitWidth(BitWidth), Assumed(ConstantRange::getEmpty(BitWidth)),
1797  Known(ConstantRange::getFull(BitWidth)) {}
1798 
1799  IntegerRangeState(const ConstantRange &CR)
1800  : BitWidth(CR.getBitWidth()), Assumed(CR),
1801  Known(getWorstState(CR.getBitWidth())) {}
1802 
1803  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
1804  static ConstantRange getWorstState(uint32_t BitWidth) {
1805  return ConstantRange::getFull(BitWidth);
1806  }
1807 
1808  /// Return the best possible representable state.
1809  static ConstantRange getBestState(uint32_t BitWidth) {
1810  return ConstantRange::getEmpty(BitWidth);
1811  }
1812  static ConstantRange getBestState(const IntegerRangeState &IRS) {
1813  return getBestState(IRS.getBitWidth());
1814  }
1815 
1816  /// Return associated values' bit width.
1817  uint32_t getBitWidth() const { return BitWidth; }
1818 
1819  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
1820  bool isValidState() const override {
1821  return BitWidth > 0 && !Assumed.isFullSet();
1822  }
1823 
1824  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
1825  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return Assumed == Known; }
1826 
1827  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
1828  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
1829  Known = Assumed;
1830  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
1831  }
1832 
1833  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
1834  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
1835  Assumed = Known;
1836  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
1837  }
1838 
1839  /// Return the known state encoding
1840  ConstantRange getKnown() const { return Known; }
1841 
1842  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
1843  ConstantRange getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
1844 
1845  /// Unite assumed range with the passed state.
1846  void unionAssumed(const ConstantRange &R) {
1847  // Don't loose a known range.
1848  Assumed = Assumed.unionWith(R).intersectWith(Known);
1849  }
1850 
1851  /// See IntegerRangeState::unionAssumed(..).
1852  void unionAssumed(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
1853  unionAssumed(R.getAssumed());
1854  }
1855 
1856  /// Unite known range with the passed state.
1857  void unionKnown(const ConstantRange &R) {
1858  // Don't loose a known range.
1859  Known = Known.unionWith(R);
1860  Assumed = Assumed.unionWith(Known);
1861  }
1862 
1863  /// See IntegerRangeState::unionKnown(..).
1864  void unionKnown(const IntegerRangeState &R) { unionKnown(R.getKnown()); }
1865 
1866  /// Intersect known range with the passed state.
1867  void intersectKnown(const ConstantRange &R) {
1868  Assumed = Assumed.intersectWith(R);
1869  Known = Known.intersectWith(R);
1870  }
1871 
1872  /// See IntegerRangeState::intersectKnown(..).
1873  void intersectKnown(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
1874  intersectKnown(R.getKnown());
1875  }
1876 
1877  /// Equality for IntegerRangeState.
1878  bool operator==(const IntegerRangeState &R) const {
1879  return getAssumed() == R.getAssumed() && getKnown() == R.getKnown();
1880  }
1881 
1882  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
1883  /// intended that only information assumed in both states will be assumed in
1884  /// this one afterwards.
1885  IntegerRangeState operator^=(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
1886  // NOTE: `^=` operator seems like `intersect` but in this case, we need to
1887  // take `union`.
1888  unionAssumed(R);
1889  return *this;
1890  }
1891 
1892  IntegerRangeState operator&=(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
1893  // NOTE: `&=` operator seems like `intersect` but in this case, we need to
1894  // take `union`.
1895  unionKnown(R);
1896  unionAssumed(R);
1897  return *this;
1898  }
1899 };

1923 /// Helper class that provides common functionality to manifest IR attributes.
1924 template <Attribute::AttrKind AK, typename BaseType>
1925 struct IRAttribute : public BaseType {
1926  IRAttribute(const IRPosition &IRP) : BaseType(IRP) {}
1927 
1928  /// See AbstractAttribute::initialize(...).
1929  virtual void initialize(Attributor &A) override {
1930  const IRPosition &IRP = this->getIRPosition();
1931  if (isa<UndefValue>(IRP.getAssociatedValue()) ||
1932  this->hasAttr(getAttrKind(), /* IgnoreSubsumingPositions */ false,
1933  &A)) {
1934  this->getState().indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
1935  return;
1936  }
1937 
1938  bool IsFnInterface = IRP.isFnInterfaceKind();
1939  const Function *FnScope = IRP.getAnchorScope();
1940  // TODO: Not all attributes require an exact definition. Find a way to
1941  // enable deduction for some but not all attributes in case the
1942  // definition might be changed at runtime, see also
1943  // http://lists.llvm.org/pipermail/llvm-dev/2018-February/121275.html.
1944  // TODO: We could always determine abstract attributes and if sufficient
1945  // information was found we could duplicate the functions that do not
1946  // have an exact definition.
1947  if (IsFnInterface && (!FnScope || !A.isFunctionIPOAmendable(*FnScope)))
1948  this->getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
1949  }
1950 
1951  /// See AbstractAttribute::manifest(...).
1952  ChangeStatus manifest(Attributor &A) override {
1953  if (isa<UndefValue>(this->getIRPosition().getAssociatedValue()))
1954  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
1955  SmallVector<Attribute, 4> DeducedAttrs;
1956  getDeducedAttributes(this->getAnchorValue().getContext(), DeducedAttrs);
1957  return IRAttributeManifest::manifestAttrs(A, this->getIRPosition(),
1958  DeducedAttrs);
1959  }
1960 
1961  /// Return the kind that identifies the abstract attribute implementation.
1962  Attribute::AttrKind getAttrKind() const { return AK; }
1963 
1964  /// Return the deduced attributes in \p Attrs.
1965  virtual void getDeducedAttributes(LLVMContext &Ctx,
1966  SmallVectorImpl<Attribute> &Attrs) const {
1967  Attrs.emplace_back(Attribute::get(Ctx, getAttrKind()));
1968  }
1969 };

1971 /// Base struct for all "concrete attribute" deductions.
1972 ///
1973 /// The abstract attribute is a minimal interface that allows the Attributor to
1974 /// orchestrate the abstract/fixpoint analysis. The design allows to hide away
1975 /// implementation choices made for the subclasses but also to structure their
1976 /// implementation and simplify the use of other abstract attributes in-flight.
1977 ///
1978 /// To allow easy creation of new attributes, most methods have default
1979 /// implementations. The ones that do not are generally straight forward, except
1980 /// `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl` which is the location of most reasoning
1981 /// associated with the abstract attribute. The update is invoked by the
1982 /// Attributor in case the situation used to justify the current optimistic
1983 /// state might have changed. The Attributor determines this automatically
1984 /// by monitoring the `Attributor::getAAFor` calls made by abstract attributes.
1985 ///
1986 /// The `updateImpl` method should inspect the IR and other abstract attributes
1987 /// in-flight to justify the best possible (=optimistic) state. The actual
1988 /// implementation is, similar to the underlying abstract state encoding, not
1989 /// exposed. In the most common case, the `updateImpl` will go through a list of
1990 /// reasons why its optimistic state is valid given the current information. If
1991 /// any combination of them holds and is sufficient to justify the current
1992 /// optimistic state, the method shall return UNCHAGED. If not, the optimistic
1993 /// state is adjusted to the situation and the method shall return CHANGED.
1994 ///
1995 /// If the manifestation of the "concrete attribute" deduced by the subclass
1996 /// differs from the "default" behavior, which is a (set of) LLVM-IR
1997 /// attribute(s) for an argument, call site argument, function return value, or
1998 /// function, the `AbstractAttribute::manifest` method should be overloaded.
1999 ///
2000 /// NOTE: If the state obtained via getState() is INVALID, thus if
2001 /// AbstractAttribute::getState().isValidState() returns false, no
2002 /// information provided by the methods of this class should be used.
2003 /// NOTE: The Attributor currently has certain limitations to what we can do.
2004 /// As a general rule of thumb, "concrete" abstract attributes should *for
2005 /// now* only perform "backward" information propagation. That means
2006 /// optimistic information obtained through abstract attributes should
2007 /// only be used at positions that precede the origin of the information
2008 /// with regards to the program flow. More practically, information can
2009 /// *now* be propagated from instructions to their enclosing function, but
2010 /// *not* from call sites to the called function. The mechanisms to allow
2011 /// both directions will be added in the future.
2012 /// NOTE: The mechanics of adding a new "concrete" abstract attribute are
2013 /// described in the file comment.
2014 struct AbstractAttribute : public IRPosition {
2015  using StateType = AbstractState;
2016 
2017  AbstractAttribute(const IRPosition &IRP) : IRPosition(IRP) {}
2018 
2019  /// Virtual destructor.
2020  virtual ~AbstractAttribute() {}
2021 
2022  /// Initialize the state with the information in the Attributor \p A.
2023  ///
2024  /// This function is called by the Attributor once all abstract attributes
2025  /// have been identified. It can and shall be used for task like:
2026  /// - identify existing knowledge in the IR and use it for the "known state"
2027  /// - perform any work that is not going to change over time, e.g., determine
2028  /// a subset of the IR, or attributes in-flight, that have to be looked at
2029  /// in the `updateImpl` method.
2030  virtual void initialize(Attributor &A) {}
2031 
2032  /// Return the internal abstract state for inspection.
2033  virtual StateType &getState() = 0;
2034  virtual const StateType &getState() const = 0;
2035 
2036  /// Return an IR position, see struct IRPosition.
2037  const IRPosition &getIRPosition() const { return *this; };
2038  IRPosition &getIRPosition() { return *this; };
2039 
2040  /// Helper functions, for debug purposes only.
2041  ///{
2042  virtual void print(raw_ostream &OS) const;
2043  void dump() const { print(dbgs()); }
2044 
2045  /// This function should return the "summarized" assumed state as string.
2046  virtual const std::string getAsStr() const = 0;
2047 
2048  /// This function should return the name of the AbstractAttribute
2049  virtual const std::string getName() const = 0;
2050 
2051  /// This function should return the address of the ID of the AbstractAttribute
2052  virtual const char *getIdAddr() const = 0;
2053  ///}
2054 
2055  /// Allow the Attributor access to the protected methods.
2056  friend struct Attributor;
2057 
2058 protected:
2059  /// Hook for the Attributor to trigger an update of the internal state.
2060  ///
2061  /// If this attribute is already fixed, this method will return UNCHANGED,
2062  /// otherwise it delegates to `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl`.
2063  ///
2064  /// \Return CHANGED if the internal state changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
2065  ChangeStatus update(Attributor &A);
2066 
2067  /// Hook for the Attributor to trigger the manifestation of the information
2068  /// represented by the abstract attribute in the LLVM-IR.
2069  ///
2070  /// \Return CHANGED if the IR was altered, otherwise UNCHANGED.
2071  virtual ChangeStatus manifest(Attributor &A) {
2072  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2073  }
2074 
2075  /// Hook to enable custom statistic tracking, called after manifest that
2076  /// resulted in a change if statistics are enabled.
2077  ///
2078  /// We require subclasses to provide an implementation so we remember to
2079  /// add statistics for them.
2080  virtual void trackStatistics() const = 0;
2081 
2082  /// The actual update/transfer function which has to be implemented by the
2083  /// derived classes.
2084  ///
2085  /// If it is called, the environment has changed and we have to determine if
2086  /// the current information is still valid or adjust it otherwise.
2087  ///
2088  /// \Return CHANGED if the internal state changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
2089  virtual ChangeStatus updateImpl(Attributor &A) = 0;
2090 
2091 private:
2092  /// Set of abstract attributes which were queried by this one. The bit encodes
2093  /// if there is an optional of required dependence.
2094  using DepTy = PointerIntPair<AbstractAttribute *, 1>;
2095  TinyPtrVector<DepTy> Deps;
2096 };

2566 /// State for dereferenceable attribute
2567 struct DerefState : AbstractState {
2568 
2569  static DerefState getBestState() { return DerefState(); }
2570  static DerefState getBestState(const DerefState &) { return getBestState(); }
2571 
2572  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
2573  static DerefState getWorstState() {
2574  DerefState DS;
2575  DS.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
2576  return DS;
2577  }
2578  static DerefState getWorstState(const DerefState &) {
2579  return getWorstState();
2580  }
2581 
2582  /// State representing for dereferenceable bytes.
2583  IncIntegerState<> DerefBytesState;
2584 
2585  /// Map representing for accessed memory offsets and sizes.
2586  /// A key is Offset and a value is size.
2587  /// If there is a load/store instruction something like,
2588  /// p[offset] = v;
2589  /// (offset, sizeof(v)) will be inserted to this map.
2590  /// std::map is used because we want to iterate keys in ascending order.
2591  std::map<int64_t, uint64_t> AccessedBytesMap;
2592 
2593  /// Helper function to calculate dereferenceable bytes from current known
2594  /// bytes and accessed bytes.
2595  ///
2596  /// int f(int *A){
2597  /// *A = 0;
2598  /// *(A+2) = 2;
2599  /// *(A+1) = 1;
2600  /// *(A+10) = 10;
2601  /// }
2602  /// ```
2603  /// In that case, AccessedBytesMap is `{0:4, 4:4, 8:4, 40:4}`.
2604  /// AccessedBytesMap is std::map so it is iterated in accending order on
2605  /// key(Offset). So KnownBytes will be updated like this:
2606  ///
2607  /// |Access | KnownBytes
2608  /// |(0, 4)| 0 -> 4
2609  /// |(4, 4)| 4 -> 8
2610  /// |(8, 4)| 8 -> 12
2611  /// |(40, 4) | 12 (break)
2612  void computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap() {
2613  int64_t KnownBytes = DerefBytesState.getKnown();
2614  for (auto &Access : AccessedBytesMap) {
2615  if (KnownBytes < Access.first)
2616  break;
2617  KnownBytes = std::max(KnownBytes, Access.first + (int64_t)Access.second);
2618  }
2619 
2620  DerefBytesState.takeKnownMaximum(KnownBytes);
2621  }
2622 
2623  /// State representing that whether the value is globaly dereferenceable.
2624  BooleanState GlobalState;
2625 
2626  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
2627  bool isValidState() const override { return DerefBytesState.isValidState(); }
2628 
2629  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
2630  bool isAtFixpoint() const override {
2631  return !isValidState() ||
2632  (DerefBytesState.isAtFixpoint() && GlobalState.isAtFixpoint());
2633  }
2634 
2635  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
2636  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
2637  DerefBytesState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
2638  GlobalState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
2639  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2640  }
2641 
2642  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
2643  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
2644  DerefBytesState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
2645  GlobalState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
2646  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2647  }
2648 
2649  /// Update known dereferenceable bytes.
2650  void takeKnownDerefBytesMaximum(uint64_t Bytes) {
2651  DerefBytesState.takeKnownMaximum(Bytes);
2652 
2653  // Known bytes might increase.
2654  computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap();
2655  }
2656 
2657  /// Update assumed dereferenceable bytes.
2658  void takeAssumedDerefBytesMinimum(uint64_t Bytes) {
2659  DerefBytesState.takeAssumedMinimum(Bytes);
2660  }
2661 
2662  /// Add accessed bytes to the map.
2663  void addAccessedBytes(int64_t Offset, uint64_t Size) {
2664  uint64_t &AccessedBytes = AccessedBytesMap[Offset];
2665  AccessedBytes = std::max(AccessedBytes, Size);
2666 
2667  // Known bytes might increase.
2668  computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap();
2669  }
2670 
2671  /// Equality for DerefState.
2672  bool operator==(const DerefState &R) const {
2673  return this->DerefBytesState == R.DerefBytesState &&
2674  this->GlobalState == R.GlobalState;
2675  }
2676 
2677  /// Inequality for DerefState.
2678  bool operator!=(const DerefState &R) const { return !(*this == R); }
2679 
2680  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator^=
2681  DerefState operator^=(const DerefState &R) {
2682  DerefBytesState ^= R.DerefBytesState;
2683  GlobalState ^= R.GlobalState;
2684  return *this;
2685  }
2686 
2687  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator+=
2688  DerefState operator+=(const DerefState &R) {
2689  DerefBytesState += R.DerefBytesState;
2690  GlobalState += R.GlobalState;
2691  return *this;
2692  }
2693 
2694  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator&=
2695  DerefState operator&=(const DerefState &R) {
2696  DerefBytesState &= R.DerefBytesState;
2697  GlobalState &= R.GlobalState;
2698  return *this;
2699  }
2700 
2701  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator|=
2702  DerefState operator|=(const DerefState &R) {
2703  DerefBytesState |= R.DerefBytesState;
2704  GlobalState |= R.GlobalState;
2705  return *this;
2706  }
2707 
2708 protected:
2709  const AANonNull *NonNullAA = nullptr;
2710 };

3026 /// An abstract interface for all memory location attributes
3027 /// (readnone/argmemonly/inaccessiblememonly/inaccessibleorargmemonly).
3028 struct AAMemoryLocation
3029  : public IRAttribute<
3030  Attribute::ReadNone,
3031  StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint32_t, 511>, AbstractAttribute>> {
3032  using MemoryLocationsKind = StateType::base_t;
3033 
3034  AAMemoryLocation(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : IRAttribute(IRP) {}
3035 
3036  /// Encoding of different locations that could be accessed by a memory
3037  /// access.
3038  enum {
3039  ALL_LOCATIONS = 0,
3040  NO_LOCAL_MEM = 1 << 0,
3041  NO_CONST_MEM = 1 << 1,
3042  NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM = 1 << 2,
3043  NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM = 1 << 3,
3044  NO_GLOBAL_MEM = NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM | NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM,
3045  NO_ARGUMENT_MEM = 1 << 4,
3046  NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM = 1 << 5,
3047  NO_MALLOCED_MEM = 1 << 6,
3048  NO_UNKOWN_MEM = 1 << 7,
3049  NO_LOCATIONS = NO_LOCAL_MEM | NO_CONST_MEM | NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM |
3050  NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM |
3051  NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_MALLOCED_MEM | NO_UNKOWN_MEM,
3052 
3053  // Helper bit to track if we gave up or not.
3054  VALID_STATE = NO_LOCATIONS + 1,
3055 
3056  BEST_STATE = NO_LOCATIONS | VALID_STATE,
3057  };
3058  static_assert(BEST_STATE == getBestState(), "Unexpected BEST_STATE value");
3059 
3060  /// Return true if we know that the associated functions has no observable
3061  /// accesses.
3062  bool isKnownReadNone() const { return isKnown(NO_LOCATIONS); }
3063 
3064  /// Return true if we assume that the associated functions has no observable
3065  /// accesses.
3066  bool isAssumedReadNone() const {
3067  return isAssumed(NO_LOCATIONS) | isAssumedStackOnly();
3068  }
3069 
3070  /// Return true if we know that the associated functions has at most
3071  /// local/stack accesses.
3072  bool isKnowStackOnly() const {
3073  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_LOCAL_MEM, true, true));
3074  }
3075 
3076  /// Return true if we assume that the associated functions has at most
3077  /// local/stack accesses.
3078  bool isAssumedStackOnly() const {
3079  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_LOCAL_MEM, true, true));
3080  }
3081 
3082  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
3083  /// inaccesible memory only (see Attribute::InaccessibleMemOnly).
3084  bool isKnownInaccessibleMemOnly() const {
3085  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM, true, true));
3086  }
3087 
3088  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
3089  /// inaccesible memory only (see Attribute::InaccessibleMemOnly).
3090  bool isAssumedInaccessibleMemOnly() const {
3091  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM, true, true));
3092  }
3093 
3094  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
3095  /// argument pointees (see Attribute::ArgMemOnly).
3096  bool isKnownArgMemOnly() const {
3097  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
3098  }
3099 
3100  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
3101  /// argument pointees (see Attribute::ArgMemOnly).
3102  bool isAssumedArgMemOnly() const {
3103  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
3104  }
3105 
3106  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
3107  /// inaccesible memory or argument pointees (see
3108  /// Attribute::InaccessibleOrArgMemOnly).
3109  bool isKnownInaccessibleOrArgMemOnly() const {
3110  return isKnown(
3111  inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
3112  }
3113 
3114  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
3115  /// inaccesible memory or argument pointees (see
3116  /// Attribute::InaccessibleOrArgMemOnly).
3117  bool isAssumedInaccessibleOrArgMemOnly() const {
3118  return isAssumed(
3119  inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
3120  }
3121 
3122  /// Return true if the underlying value may access memory through arguement
3123  /// pointers of the associated function, if any.
3124  bool mayAccessArgMem() const { return !isAssumed(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM); }
3125 
3126  /// Return true if only the memory locations specififed by \p MLK are assumed
3127  /// to be accessed by the associated function.
3128  bool isAssumedSpecifiedMemOnly(MemoryLocationsKind MLK) const {
3129  return isAssumed(MLK);
3130  }
3131 
3132  /// Return the locations that are assumed to be not accessed by the associated
3133  /// function, if any.
3134  MemoryLocationsKind getAssumedNotAccessedLocation() const {
3135  return getAssumed();
3136  }
3137 
3138  /// Return the inverse of location \p Loc, thus for NO_XXX the return
3139  /// describes ONLY_XXX. The flags \p AndLocalMem and \p AndConstMem determine
3140  /// if local (=stack) and constant memory are allowed as well. Most of the
3141  /// time we do want them to be included, e.g., argmemonly allows accesses via
3142  /// argument pointers or local or constant memory accesses.
3143  static MemoryLocationsKind
3144  inverseLocation(MemoryLocationsKind Loc, bool AndLocalMem, bool AndConstMem) {
3145  return NO_LOCATIONS & ~(Loc | (AndLocalMem ? NO_LOCAL_MEM : 0) |
3146  (AndConstMem ? NO_CONST_MEM : 0));
3147  };
3148 
3149  /// Return the locations encoded by \p MLK as a readable string.
3150  static std::string getMemoryLocationsAsStr(MemoryLocationsKind MLK);
3151 
3152  /// Simple enum to distinguish read/write/read-write accesses.
3153  enum AccessKind {
3154  NONE = 0,
3155  READ = 1 << 0,
3156  WRITE = 1 << 1,
3157  READ_WRITE = READ | WRITE,
3158  };
3159 
3160  /// Check \p Pred on all accesses to the memory kinds specified by \p MLK.
3161  ///
3162  /// This method will evaluate \p Pred on all accesses (access instruction +
3163  /// underlying accessed memory pointer) and it will return true if \p Pred
3164  /// holds every time.
3165  virtual bool checkForAllAccessesToMemoryKind(
3166  function_ref<bool(const Instruction *, const Value *, AccessKind,
3167  MemoryLocationsKind)>
3168  Pred,
3169  MemoryLocationsKind MLK) const = 0;
3170 
3171  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
3172  static AAMemoryLocation &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
3173  Attributor &A);
3174 
3175  /// See AbstractState::getAsStr().
3176  const std::string getAsStr() const override {

3178  }
3179

3181  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAMemoryLocation"; }
3182
